Zealots of free trade
From Cambridge — Recently, I was invited to guest lecture in the globalization courses of two Harvard colleagues. "I must warn you."
One of them warned me in advance: "These students are all strong proponents of globalization."
He once asked the students in the first class to choose between free trade and import restrictions, and over 90% favored the former.
And that was even before he had begun to teach the magical effects of comparative advantage.
We know that using the same question to survey representative samples in real surveys — rather than Harvard students — would yield a completely different result.
In the United States, the ratio of opponents to supporters of trade restrictions is 2:1.
But the answers of Harvard students would not be particularly surprising.
Because those with higher technology and better education are often more inclined to support free trade than blue-collar workers.
And perhaps these Harvard students have already anticipated their future prospects and made their decisions accordingly.
Or perhaps, they actually don't understand how trade works.
After all, when I met with them, I deliberately asked the same question in a different format and emphasized the distributional effects that trade might produce.
The consensus in favor of fair trade completely disappeared, even more rapidly than I had anticipated.
At the beginning, I first asked everyone if they agreed to participate in a particularly magical experiment.
I selected Nicholas and John as volunteers and told them that I had a way to make $200 disappear from Nicholas's account—poof!—while simultaneously adding $300 to John's account, and through the wonders of social engineering, this class as a whole would gain an additional $100 in value.
So would they allow me to perform this little trick?
Only a small portion firmly agreed, many were uncertain, and even more opposed the implementation of this change.
The consensus supporting free trade completely disappeared, even more rapidly than I had anticipated.
Clearly, the students found this form of significant income redistribution difficult to tolerate, even when the overall economic pie had been greatly expanded.
I then asked why the majority of them almost instinctively supported free trade, which actually also leads to a similar — indeed even a more significant — redistribution of wealth from losers to winners.
The students looked stunned.
I then said, let's assume that Nicholas and John each own a small competing company.
John works harder, saves and invests more, and produces better products, so he not only ends up $300 ahead of Nicholas but also drives Nicholas's company out of the market, causing him a $200 loss.
So how many students supported this change?
This time, the majority voted in favor — in fact, only Nicholas disagreed!
I then presented another assumption directly related to international trade.
If John drove Nicholas out of the market by importing high-quality products from Germany?
Or outsourcing business processes to China, where labor rights are not yet fully established?
Or employing child labor in Indonesia?
Approval for the change decreased sequentially with the above options.
Moreover, technological innovation can also, like trade, leave certain groups in a more disadvantaged position—what is your stance on this?
Only a few students were willing to restrain technological development.
For almost everyone, banning the production of light bulbs to save the jobs of candle makers is a ridiculous idea.
Therefore, the students are not necessarily opposed to redistribution, but only to certain specific forms of it.
Like most of us, they all focus on the fairness of the process.
If we are to judge the results of redistribution, we must know the objective circumstances that produced such results.
We do not resent the enormous wealth of Bill Gates or Warren Buffett, even though some of their competitors have never had an easy time, probably because they and their competitors all operate under the same basic rules and face very similar opportunities and challenges.
But if Gates and Buffett had become rich not through their own intelligence and effort, but through fraud, violation of labor laws, environmental destruction, or by exploiting subsidies from foreign governments, our views would be entirely different.
If we cannot tolerate redistribution achieved through the violation of moral standards universally observed domestically, on what grounds can we feel at ease simply because it involves international transactions?
Similarly, when we expect redistribution effects to achieve equality in the long run and everyone will ultimately benefit, we are likely to pay little attention to the transfer of income.
This is also why we believe that despite technology causing short-term negative consequences for some people, we are still willing to promote its development.
On the other hand, when trade continuously impacts the same group — low-educated blue-collar workers — we once again become concerned about globalization.
But many economists ignore these obvious differences.
They tend to attribute their concerns about globalization to foolish, self-serving protectionist motives or ignorance, without realizing that the most important issue is actually a moral one.
Because they fail to recognize that international trade — although not often — sometimes leads to redistribution consequences that we cannot accept domestically, these economists are also unable to appropriately engage in public discourse.
How can they then strongly advocate for trade if it is morally indefensible?
When globalization occasionally raises a thorny issue related to the legitimization of redistribution effects, we should not reflexively respond with trade restrictions.
There are many difficult trade-offs to consider, including the fact that globalization may cause more severe wealth deprivation for people in other places than for American victims.
But democratic countries should have a more appropriate discussion on this and make conscious, more thoughtful decisions.
Such an approach, which is infatuated with globalization merely because it has expanded the pie, will inevitably erode the legitimacy of globalization itself in the long run.
